data</fgdcGeoform></presForm></idCitation><idAbs>The Horizon table lists the horizon(s) and related data for the referenced map unit component. If the horizon thickness is greater than zero (low=5, RV=8, high=12), the horizon exists everywhere this component occurs. If the horizon thickness includes zero (low=0, RV=1, high=3), the horizon may exist in some places, but not in other places. Horizons that have two distinct parts, such as E/B or E&Bt horizons, are recorded twice. data</fgdcGeoform></presForm></idCitation><idAbs>The Horizon Texture Group table lists the range of textures for the referenced horizon as a concatenation of horizon texture and texture modifier(s). For example, a horizon that is gravelly loamy sand in some places and gravelly loamy coarse sand in other places is shown as GR-LS on one row and GR-LCOS on another row in this table. The row with the typically occurring texture is identified as the RV row. Stratified textures are shown in one row. For example, a horizon that is stratified gravelly loamy fine sand and cobbly coarse sand is shown as SR- GR-LFS CB-COS on one row and the Stratified? column for that row is marked "yes". <metadata><idinfo><citation><citeinfo><origin>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</origin><pubdate>20140120</pubdate><title>Gridded Soil Survey Geographic (gSSURGO) Database for xxSTATExx</title><edition>FY2014</edition><geoform>vector and raster digital map data and tabular digital data</geoform><serinfo><sername>gSSURGO</sername><issue>FY2014</issue></serinfo><pubinfo><pubplace>Fort Worth, Texas</pubplace><publish>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</publish></pubinfo><onlink>URL:http://datagateway.nrcs.usda.gov</onlink></citeinfo></citation><descript><abstract>This dataset is called the Gridded SSURGO (gSSURGO) Database and is derived from the Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database. SSURGO is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey (NCSS) in accordance with NCSS mapping standards. The tabular data represent the soil attributes, and are derived from properties and characteristics stored in the National Soil Information System (NASIS). The gSSURGO data were prepared by merging traditional SSURGO digital vector map and tabular data into State-wide extents, and adding a state-wide gridded map layer derived from the polygon layer. The gridded map layer is offered in an ArcGIS file geodatabase raster format. The raster map data have a 10 meter cell size that approximates the vector polygons in an Albers Equal Area projection. Each cell (and polygon) is linked to a map unit identifier called the map unit key. The unique map unit key is used to link to raster cells and polygons to mapunit and muaggatt attribute tables.</abstract><purpose>The Gridded SSURGO dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The dataset consists of soils data in raster, vector and attribute tables. The raster map layer data can be readily combined with other national, regional, and local raster layers, e.g., National Land Cover Database (NLCD), the National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS) Crop Data Layer, or the National Elevation Dataset (NED).</purpose></descript><timeperd><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>20121015</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo><current>publication date</current></timeperd><status><progress>In work</progress><update>Annually</update></status><spdom><bounding><westbc>-174.837525</westbc><eastbc>-123.540711</eastbc><northbc>65.978601</northbc><southbc>54.199787</southbc></bounding></spdom><keywords><place><placekt>Counties and County Equivalents of the States of the United States and the District of Columbia (FIPS Pub 6-3)</placekt><placekey>United States of America</placekey><placekey>USA</placekey><placekey>xxSTATExx</placekey><placekey>xxSURVEYSxx</placekey></place><theme><themekey>soils, raster, Geospatial Data Gateway, gridded, Soil Survey, GDG, gSSURGO, SSURGO</themekey></theme></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>The U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, should be acknowledged as the data source in products derived from these data. This dataset is not designed for use as a primary regulatory tool in permitting or siting decisions, but may be used as a reference source. This is public information and may be interpreted by organizations, agencies, units of government, or others based on needs; however, they are responsible for the appropriate application. Federal, State, or local regulatory bodies are not to reassign to the Natural Resources Conservation Service any authority for the decisions that they make. The Natural Resources Conservation Service will not perform any evaluations of these maps for purposes related solely to State or local regulatory programs. Digital data files are periodically updated. Files are dated, and users are responsible for obtaining the latest version of the data.</useconst><ptcontac><cntinfo><cntorgp><cntorg>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</cntorg></cntorgp><cntaddr><addrtype>mailing</addrtype><address>100 Centennial Mall North</address><address>Federal Building, Room 152</address><city>Lincoln</city><state>NE</state><postal>68508-3866</postal></cntaddr><cntvoice>402 437 5499</cntvoice><cntemail>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</cntemail></cntinfo></ptcontac><datacred>Soil Survey Staff. Gridded Soil Survey Geographic (gSSURGO) Database for xxSTATExx. United States Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service. Available online at http://datagateway.nrcs.usda.gov/. xxTODAYxx (xxFYxx official release).</datacred><native>Microsoft Windows 7 Version 6.1 (Build 7601) Service Pack 1; Esri ArcGIS 10.1.1.3143</native></idinfo><dataqual><logic>The raster dataset uses the topologically correct vector SSURGO dataset for its source. Overlaps and gaps were eliminated from the polygon featureclasses. The tests of logical consistency are performed using vendor software.</logic><complete>The data are being generalized during the vector to raster conversion. The acreage total of the cells will differ from the acreage total of the polygons. The SSURGO raster was also aligned to the National Land Cover Database (NLCD).</complete><lineage><srcinfo><srccite><citeinfo><origin>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</origin><title>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database for Soil Survey Areas</title><geoform>vector digital data</geoform><pubinfo><pubplace>Kansas City, Missouri</pubplace><publish>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</publish></pubinfo></citeinfo></srccite><srcscale>0</srcscale><typesrc>onLine</typesrc><srctime><timeinfo><rngdates><begdate>19950101</begdate><enddate>present</enddate></rngdates></timeinfo><srccurr>publication date</srccurr></srctime><srccitea>NRCS</srccitea><srccontr>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data from Web Soil Survey</srccontr></srcinfo><srcinfo><srccite><citeinfo><origin>U.S. Department of the Interior, U.S. Geological Survey</origin><pubdate>20060101</pubdate><title>National Land Cover Database 2006</title><geoform>raster digital data</geoform></citeinfo></srccite><typesrc>onLine</typesrc><srctime><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>20060101</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo><srccurr>publication date</srccurr></srctime><srccitea>NLCD</srccitea><srccontr>cell alignment layer</srccontr></srcinfo><procstep><procdesc>This dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to data in the gSSURGO attribute tables, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>State-wide file geodatabases (ESRI) were exported from the January, 2014 SSURGO downloads from Web Soil Survey. Software used for all processes was ArcGIS 10.1. All existing SSURGO features and attributes were selected by querying the online Soil Data Access database to identify non-MLRA (Major Land Resource Area) soil survey areas that intersect this particular 'State or Territory'. The spatial data were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to Albers Equal Area Conic.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>Metadata was updated.</procdesc><srcused>NLCD</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>An integer version of the mapunit key was created and used to generate the raster layer. After the raster attribute table was created, the character mapunit key was regenerated from those integer values.</procdesc><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>A 10 meter file geodatabase raster layer was created by converting the 'MUPOLYGON' feature class from feature to raster using 'PolygonToRaster' with the 'MAXIMUM_COMBINED_AREA' option in ArcGIS 10.x. The raster layer was aligned to the NLCD raster. Raster statistics, pyramids and an attribute table containing mapunit key were created.</procdesc><srcused>NLCD</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep></lineage></dataqual><spdoinfo><direct>Vector</direct><ptvctinf><sdtsterm><sdtstype>GT-polygon composed of chains</sdtstype><ptvctcnt>0</ptvctcnt></sdtsterm></ptvctinf><rastinfo><rasttype>Grid Cell</rasttype></rastinfo></spdoinfo><eainfo><overview xmlns=""><eaover>Each pixel may be dominated by a single soil or miscellaneous area component plus allowable similar or dissimilar soils, or they can be geographic mixtures of groups of soils or soils and miscellaneous areas.
The map unit key (mukey) uniquely identifies the map unit of a pixel. The map unit key is used to link to information in the National Soil Information System tables.
Map units are described by the National Soil Information System database. This attribute database gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and the properties for each soil. The database contains both estimated and measured data on the physical and chemical soil properties and soil interpretations for engineering, water management, recreation, agronomic, woodland, range, and wildlife uses of the soil.
The mukey column and value was added to the raster attribute table to facilitate joins with the attribute data.</eaover><eadetcit>U.S. Department of Agriculture. 1999. The dataset consists of soils data in raster format from Digital Soil Mapping (DSM) projects along with associated attribute tables. The raster map layer data can be readily combined with other national, regional, and local raster layers, e.g., National Land Cover Database (NLCD), the National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS) Crop Data Layer, or the National Elevation Dataset (NED).</idPurp><idAbs><DIV STYLE="text-align:Left;"><DIV><DIV><P><SPAN>The Raster Soil Survey (RSS) database is a representation of soil survey work completed using digital soil mapping methodologies. Where available, this data represents the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The associated data represents Raster Soil Survey class data, available in this state. The tabular data represent the soil attributes, and are derived from properties and characteristics stored in the National Soil Information System (NASIS). The spatial data rendered in the geodatabase result from Raster Soil Survey - Project Mapping. Raster Soil Survey is a reference to products of soil survey work completed using digital soil mapping methodologies. The gridded map layer is offered in an ArcGIS file geodatabase raster format. The raster map data have a 10 meter cell size that approximates aligns with the Gridded Soil Survey Geographic (gSSURGO) Database. Raster Soil Survey data represents the most detailed soil survey information for a given area within the Gridded National Soil Geographic Database (gNATSGO) product. Each cell is linked to a map unit identifier called the map unit key. The unique map unit key is used to link to raster cells to mapunit and aggregated attribute tables. Additional information on methods, process and standards for Digital Soil Mapping and Raster Soil Survey can be found in Chapter 5 of the Soil Survey Manual, Part 648 of the National Soil Survey Handbook, and the USDA-NRCS Digital Soil Mapping Website online at https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/portal/nrcs/detail/soils/survey/geo/?cid=stelprdb1254424.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idCredit>Soil Survey Staff.
